Month = {NOV},
Abstract = {We study the security of Cyber-Physical Systems (CPS) in the context of
   the supervisory control layer. Specifically, we propose a general model
   of a CPS attacker in the framework of discrete event systems and
   investigate the problem of synthesizing an attack strategy for a given
   feedback control system. Our model captures a class of deception
   attacks, where the attacker has the ability to hijack a subset of sensor
   readings and mislead the supervisor, with the goal of inducing the
   system into an undesirable state. We utilize a game-like discrete
   transition structure, called Insertion-Deletion Attack structure (IDA),
   to capture the interaction between the supervisor and the environment
   (which includes the system and the attacker). We show how to use IDAs to
   synthesize three different types of successful stealthy attacks, i.e.,
   attacks that avoid detection from the supervisor and cause damage to the
   system. (C) 2020 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.},
